            <scopecontent id="aspace_6c808f8c47ac46defdfc8f14c544f4c2">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>The series contains documents and ephemera, dating between 1899 and 1947, which record the development and operation of various companies in Alaska and the Yukon Territory. The materials explain how life and business could flourish despite travel and communications difficulties caused by the rugged terrain, the scattered settlements, and the severe weather. A substantial amount of material pertains to the various rail and river enterprises owned by the firm White Pass and Yukon Route and reveals how the company perceived its role in the territories and how it viewed its employees. The time rolls and distribution of labor books trace details such as the number of hours worked by employees, rate of hourly wages, and occupations, and thus constitute an important resource for labor history.</p>
            </scopecontent>
